From af2c67868a6d8c58b66c2fb37c453e8ca609734f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: VyOS LS1046A maintainers <ask20@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: Wed, 13 May 2026 03:26:01 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fman: add host-command transport for in-FMan microcode

Synchronous request/response transport between the kernel and a microcode running inside the FMan policer/parser/keygen complex (e.g. NXP proprietary 210 fast-path microcode used by ASK2 - see specs/ask2-rewrite-spec.md). The transport itself - command/response MURAM slots, doorbell ringing, IRQ-driven completion, mutex serialisation - is microcode-agnostic; opcode-specific encoding lives in the consumer.

Public API per spec sec 3.4: int fmd_host_cmd(struct fman *, u8 opcode, const void *req, size_t req_len, void *resp, size_t resp_buf_len, size_t *resp_len_out); plus void fmd_host_cmd_complete(struct fman *) callable from the microcode-specific IRQ status handler. Both EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL.

Per-FMan state is created lazily on the first fmd_host_cmd() call against a given fman, claims a 1024-byte request slot and a 1024-byte response slot from MURAM via the new fman_get_muram() accessor, and is keyed by the struct fman pointer in a small hidden registry list (single FMan on LS1046A, dual-FMan SoCs would also work).

Hardware-probe gap (see specs/ask2-rewrite-spec.md sec 12.7): the microcode-specific FPM doorbell register offset and the IRQ status mask are not in the public FMan TRM. The two helpers fmd_host_cmd_ring_doorbell() and fmd_host_cmd_arm_irq() are the only place the implementation touches microcode-specific MMIO; both currently return -ENXIO. The hardware-probe PR (PR13 in plans/ASK2-IMPLEMENTATION.md) fills in the doorbell offset, the IRQ binding, and the call-site for fmd_host_cmd_complete(). The wire-format framing, MURAM region claim, mutex/completion serialisation, and 100 ms response-timeout logic are all live and link-validated as of this commit.

No behaviour change for existing in-tree users: the new accessor fman_get_muram() is additive; the new fman_host_cmd.c is a separate translation unit added to fsl_dpaa_fman.ko; no existing dpaa/fman code path is modified.
